<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 7.3.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
<h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. Aligning Learning with an Implementation Model</h3>

<h3>Implementation Model</h3>
	  <p>The Collaborative Improvement and Innovation Network (CoIIN) model provides a relevant framework for creating responsive and effective MCH systems. This model brings together interdisciplinary teams to test innovative strategies and build evidence for optimizing high-quality, cost-effective, and family-centered care.<sup>1</sup></p>
	  <p>The CoIIN approach is distinct from other improvement models because it consists of multiple interdisciplinary teams that each implement the full spectrum of change steps - identifying problems, determining interventions, applying them, and evaluating results using evidence-based processes such as Plan-Do-Study-Act cycles. These teams then share their findings with one another so that successes spread throughout the collaborative and eventually to the wider field.<sup>1</sup></p>
	  <p>There are<em> five key areas</em> <em>of action</em>, including: (1) Interdisciplinary collaboration with family representatives as full partners, (2) Common goals while allowing teams to address local contexts, (3) Shared measurement systems to monitor progress in real-time, (4) Continuous communication between participants, and (5) A central support structure to coordinate efforts. </p>
	  <p>The CoIIN model is guided by core values including accountability to families, transparency in sharing both successes and challenges, and ensuring all team members participate regardless of their professional background.</p>
	 <p><img src="../../images/smart-implementation-framework-7b.png"  alt="Implementation Framework" /></p>
