  <h3><i class="mch-compass-2"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-compass-3.jpg" alt="Image of Compass" class="right ppic" />RELATE. Strategies to Enable Effective Implementation</h3>

<p>In this section, reflect on how you can implement this competency in your daily work. To help with this process, review these <strong>five implementation strategies</strong>.</p>
<h3>Tiered Approach</h3>
<p>These implementation strategies follow a <strong>tiered approach of widening circles of influence</strong>. Through this approach, MCH leaders utilize resources and tools to activate change within their organization, which in turn incorporates partners through its systems of influence. Together, changes may be implemented to affect specific target populations and the MCH community in general. </p>
<p><img src="../../images/spheres-of-influence.png" alt="Implementation Model" width="1956" height="700"/></p>
<h3>Implementation Strategies</h3>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> <strong>Self-Reflection Strategy. </strong>How to advance yourself as an MCH leader.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Advance Yourself as an MCH Leader (Self-Reflection Strategy)</strong>. Identify your personal strengths and areas of growth by taking 5 minutes to register/log-in to the MCH Navigator's <a href="../../assessment/index.php">Self-Assessment</a> and answer questions related to Competency 7: Creating Responsive and Effective MCH Systems.</p></div><button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>Information Strategy. </strong>How to find and use tools to help you.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Find and Use Tools to Help You (Information Strategy)</strong>. There are numerous resources in the field that address creating responsive and effective MCH systems, but knowing where to start can be challenging. The National Center for Education in Maternal and Child Health (NCEMCH) has developed valuable tools to support your work, including a <a href="https://www.mchnavigator.org/trainings/systems-integration.php">Training Spotlight on Systems Integration</a>, and a <a href= "https://www.mchnavigator.org/trainings/change-management.php">Resource Brief on Change Management.</a> These foundational tools can help you incorporate systems thinking into your daily work and create more responsive and effective services for MCH populations. </p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-university"></i> <strong>Organizational Strategy. </strong>How to activate your organization.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Activate Your Organization (Organizational Strategy)</strong>. Assessing organizational structures, processes, and capabilities is a necessary and systematic way to plan for and implement improved MCH systems within your organization. <a href="https://www.fsg.org/tools-and-resources/water-systems-change-action-learning-exercise">The Water of Systems Change Action Learning Exercise</a> from FSG Consulting is designed to help individuals think systematically about strategic transformation, explore underlying organizational dynamics, and determine how they and their organizations can pursue meaningful, structured improvements in a disciplined and holistic manner. Building strong systems-oriented practices in service delivery is essential to respond to changing population needs, improve service quality and health outcomes, and meet program requirements. The Center for Public Health Systems Science's <a href="https://cphss.wustl.edu/items/program-sustainability-assessment-tool-project/">Program Sustainability Assessment Tool </a>offers comprehensive guidance on evaluating and implementing sustainable practices across multiple domains, including strategic planning, program adaptation, communications, and organizational capacity.</p>
</div>

<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-cogs"></i> <strong>Systems Strategy. </strong>How to incorporate partners.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>How to Incorporate Partners (Systems Strategy)</strong>. The <a href="https://ctb.ku.edu/en/table-of-contents/overview/models-for-community-health-and-development/collective-impact/main">Collective Impact Framework</a> provides a comprehensive approach for organizations to advance coordinated efforts while serving MCH populations. The framework emphasizes common agenda, shared measurement, mutually reinforcing activities, continuous communication, and backbone support.</p>
</div>
    <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-globe"></i> <strong>Community Strategy. </strong>How to engage your communities.</button>
<div class="panel">
  <p><strong>H</strong><strong>ow to Engage Your Communities. </strong>Community engagement is the process of working collaboratively with groups of people affiliated by geographic proximity, special interest, or similar situations to address issues affecting their wellbeing. The MCH Evidence Center's <a href="https://www.mchevidence.org/documents/briefs/TA-Brief-Community-Engagement.pdf"> Community Engagement Technical Assistance Brief</a> provides a framework for meaningful community participation, including guidance on partner identification, capacity building, and creating sustainable partnerships.</p>
</div>
</div>  

      
<h2><i class="mch-light-bulb"></i> 7.3.2 PRACTICE</h2>
	  <div class="evidenceBorder">
	  <h3><i class="mch-bookmarks"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-reflect.jpg" alt="Image of Thought Bubble" class="right ppic" />REFLECT. Staying Motivated</h3>
	  <p>As you work through your growth in this competency, it&rsquo;s important to stay motivated. Here are some tips to help you maintain focus and productivity along the way:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Keep a time log</strong>. 
          Keep a time log so that you can see how much time you&rsquo;re spending on different tasks. You&rsquo;ll be surprised at the results! Keep the log for at least three days, writing down every single thing you do each day. By reviewing your time log, you&rsquo;ll be able to minimize or eliminate low-value activities.</li>
        <li><strong>Break the material down into chunks</strong>. 
          A major cause of procrastination is that the task ahead seems overwhelming.<br>
          That&rsquo;s when you need to &ldquo;chunk down.&rdquo; Break down each task into small chunks. Assign yourself a certain number of those chunks each day. Suddenly, you&rsquo;re no longer faced with a scary task, but rather a series of manageable chunks.</li>
        <li><strong>Reward yourself</strong>. 
          Every time you complete one or two chunks, reward yourself with a short period of relaxation. It could be five minutes on your favorite smartphone game, a short walk, or playing the guitar. Rewarding yourself with short and enjoyable breaks is a key part of the &ldquo;chunking down&rdquo; technique.</li>
      </ul>
      <p><img src="../../images/mch-smart-motivation-7.jpeg" width="1024" height="512" alt="Motivational image" /> </p>
	  </div>
